teliospores and teliospore pedicels whose apical parts swell noticeably in fluids (Fig. 19 ). The host plant could not be determined to the species but probably belongs to sections Jussieua or Vitifoliae of Jatropha subgen. Cnidoscolus. As far as the author knows, only the teliospores of the rust have been described so far. The Argentine specimen also revealed spermogonia, aecia, and uredinia. Uromyces cnidoscoli is thus an autoecious macrocyclic species. Unfortunately, most of the aecia were old or heavily parasitised by Tuberculina sp. Therefore, the description of the aecia and aeciospores is provisional: Aecia aecidioid, in small, dense groups abaxially or adaxially on leaves, more rarely on stalks and fruit capsules, on brownish spots of the host tissue that later become necrotic, with frail white short peridium that hardly emerges from the aecidial cavity, aeciospores catenulate, broadly ellipsoidal to subglobose, often slightly angular, 23-31 x 18-24 µm,

teliospores but a few tiny sori bearing only teliospores also develop. No pycnia were found on leaf lesions. The infected leaf rachis, normally up to 1mm diam., is swollen to 2mm, with several small raised lesions 4-6 x 2mm. In some cases, where larger lesions up to 20mm long are present, the rachis is bent to varying degrees (Fig. 2D), or distorted into a loop (Fig. 2A). On branches, infection begins as slightly raised, brown, elliptical lesions 1.5-3 x 1-2 mm. These develop into raised, oval to elongated galls along one side of the branch, ranging from 5-15 x 3-6mm and 2mm high on thinner (2-4mm) branches, to large elongated oval galls 18-55 x 8-15mm, raised 3 (-4)mm above the general branch surface (Fig. 2 B, D, E). Considerable distortion and twisting may occur, especially on thinner branches, and in these cases, lesions are generally concentrated on the outside of the bends. Thorns on twigs and branches may be partially incorporated into galls. Rachis, twig and branch lesions and galls bear pycnia towards their centre (Fig. 2E), seen most readily in younger galls, and a ring of aecial uredinia, or occasionally telia, develops around them as lesions and galls enlarge. The shallow conical sori on branch and rachis lesions are at first covered by a raised, shiny, dark brown layer of host cuticle, epidermis and cortical cells to 50µm

In some cases, where larger lesions up to 20mm long are present, the rachis is bent to varying degrees (Fig. 2D), or distorted into a loop (Fig. 2A). On branches, infection begins as slightly raised, brown, elliptical lesions 1.5-3 x 1-2 mm. These develop into raised, oval to elongated galls along one side of the branch, ranging from 5-15 x 3-6mm and 2mm high on thinner (2-4mm) branches, to large elongated oval galls 18-55 x 8-15mm, raised 3 (-4)mm above the general branch surface (Fig. 2 B, D, E). Considerable distortion and twisting may occur, especially on thinner branches, and in these cases, lesions are generally concentrated on the outside of the bends. Thorns on twigs and branches may be partially incorporated into galls. Rachis, twig and branch lesions and galls bear pycnia towards their centre (Fig. 2E), seen most readily in younger galls, and a ring of aecial uredinia, or occasionally telia, develops around them as lesions and galls enlarge. The shallow conical sori on branch and rachis lesions are at first covered by a raised, shiny, dark brown layer of host cuticle, epidermis and cortical cells to 50µm

The host plant could not be determined to the species but probably belongs to sections Jussieua or Vitifoliae of Jatropha subgen. Cnidoscolus. As far as the author knows, only the teliospores of the rust have been described so far. The Argentine specimen also revealed spermogonia, aecia, and uredinia. Uromyces cnidoscoli is thus an autoecious macrocyclic species. Unfortunately, most of the aecia were old or heavily parasitised by Tuberculina sp. Therefore, the description of the aecia and aeciospores is provisional: Aecia aecidioid, in small, dense groups abaxially or adaxially on leaves, more rarely on stalks and fruit capsules, on brownish spots of the host tissue that later become necrotic, with frail white short peridium that hardly emerges from the aecidial cavity, aeciospores catenulate, broadly ellipsoidal to subglobose, often slightly angular, 23-31 x 18-24 µm,
